<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Notes_for_Week_3:_3.2._Producer_Surplus_and_the_Supply_Curve">Notes for Week 3: <b>3.2. Producer Surplus and the Supply Curve</b></span></h2>
<p><i>Producer Surplus = Price - Willingness to Sell</i></p>
<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Key_Ideas:"><b>Key Ideas:</b></span></h2>
<ul>
<li><p>Cost is another word for the supply curve.  How many consumers are willing to buy a good at different prices.</p></li>
<li><p>Between the price and the supply curve (aka left of the supply curve under the price)
<a href="/wiki/images/d/dd/3.2_Producer_Surplus_and_the_Supply_Curve_1.jpg" class="image"><img alt="3.2 Producer Surplus and the Supply Curve 1.jpg" src="/wiki/images/d/dd/3.2_Producer_Surplus_and_the_Supply_Curve_1.jpg" width="571" height="535" /></a></p></li>
<li><p>Direct relationship between the price and the area of the producer surplus
<ul><li><i>Price increase= more Producer Surplus ($30 level vs $20)</i>
</li><li><a href="/wiki/images/4/43/3.2_Producer_Surplus_and_the_Supply_Curve_3.jpg" class="image"><img alt="3.2 Producer Surplus and the Supply Curve 3.jpg" src="/wiki/images/4/43/3.2_Producer_Surplus_and_the_Supply_Curve_3.jpg" width="596" height="539" /></a>
</li><li><i> Price decrease= less Producer Surplus ($10 level vs $20)</i>.
</li><li><a href="/wiki/images/c/c8/3.2_Producer_Surplus_and_the_Supply_Curve_2.jpg" class="image"><img alt="3.2 Producer Surplus and the Supply Curve 2.jpg" src="/wiki/images/c/c8/3.2_Producer_Surplus_and_the_Supply_Curve_2.jpg" width="554" height="530" /></a></p></li>
</li></ul>
</ul>
<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Producer_Surplus_is_the_inverse_of_Consumer_Surplus"><b>Producer Surplus is the inverse of Consumer Surplus</b></span></h2>
<ul>
<li>The more something costs, the less consumers want to consume it. </li>
<li>The less something costs, the less producers want to produce it.</li>
</ul>
<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Producer_welfare_is_a_change_in_producer_surplus"><b>Producer welfare is a change in producer surplus</b></span></h2>
<p>-If producer surplus (PS) increases, then producer welfare increases, and if PS decreases, then producer welfare decreases.</p>
<p></p>

